      "content": "You can argue that segregation was a deliberate strategy to minimize social friction by creating insulated, self-regulating environments. The premise here is that diverse populations, when forced into close proximity, inevitably lead to resource competition and cultural clashes, which destabilizes the entire social fabric. By maintaining separate spheres, proponents claimed that each community could develop its own harmonious rhythm and social order, free from the perceived chaos of mixing. This framing suggests that stability is best achieved through controlled separation rather than forced, turbulent integration.",
